Project 1: Descriptive statistics on socio-demographic profile of Hungary

Research question

We are specially interested in correlations and patterns among marital status and educational years and place of residence of Hungarians. We also interested in a further consequences of such patterns.

Thus, our research question is the following: Does the education and place of residence influence on marital age?

Creating function for defining mode (note,that it is exclude NA values)

function.mode <- function(x) {
  theonly <- na.omit(unique(x))
  theonly[which.max(tabulate(match(x, theonly,  nomatch = NA_integer_, incomparables = NULL)))]
}

In the first graph we can observe the distribution of educational years citizens have. Therefore, this graph may show us the common educational tendencies in the country. On this graph we see that it is left-skewed, so the most people in Hungary study approximately 11 years, therefore, many people do not continue their education after graduation from school. It also has a quite high kurtosis, so we can say that is nor normally distributed. Graph also seems to be symmetrical, as the amount of participants with a small and big numbers of education years is quite tiny.

Finally, our last graph shows how different marital statuses varies in various types of residences. There is some interesting results in cases of big city and small town. We may see that in big cities and its suburbs the number of divorced and dissolved people (that is ~45 & ~20) is higher number of people who lost their partner (about 37 & 3). While in small towns and villages it is in contrast higher. So, we may assume, that inhabitants of smaller cities are less become lone by their will. We also can observe, that the highest number of legally married (red one) is presented in a village, and the smallest (~2) in the big city. So, probably the tendency of civil union is more spread in a big cities.

Conclusion

To sum up, our graphs show some main tendencies in socio-demographic position of Hungarian citizens. From the data we may see that the majority of citizens have only school education and have not studied more than 11 years. Speaking about marriage, people do not get married late, mostly in 20-25 years old (however, female on average are younger than males in their first marriage). We also have learned that families in Hungary do mostly live in small towns or even villages, and only the little proportion of people live in the big cities, which is also an interesting point. This way, it gives us a certain right to say that time spent on education and place of residence have an impact on marital status and age of the first marriage of Hungarians.

Project 2: Basic Tests

Research area

As it was in our previous project, we conducted a small study on socio-demographic characteristics of Hungary population.

Chi-squared Test

First, we start with data export and its updating for Chi-squared Test

Hungary_chi <- Hungary [c("gndr", "emplrel")]

For Chi-squared test two categorical variables are needed. In our case these are: gndr (gender of a person) - nominal, emplrel (employment form -> whether the person is an employee/self-employed/working for own family buisness) - nominal

Their values are specified below: Gender of a person:

table(Hungary_chi$gndr)
## 
##   Male Female 
##    706    955

Employment form

table(Hungary_chi$emplrel)
## 
##                        Employee                   Self-employed 
##                            1396                              92 
## Working for own family business 
##                              29

Next, we specify the hypotheses: H0 = For the population of Hungarian citizens, gender of a person and his/her employment form are independent. H1 = For the population of Hungarian citizens, gender of a person and his/her employment form are dependent

We also formulate a substantive hypothesis: we expect to see the association between gender of a person and his/her employment form (whether a person is an employee, self-employed or working for family business). In particular, we expect to see more self-employed people among the group of males and more generally employed among the females.

When the variables are defined and hypotheses are spelled out, we construct a Stacked bar plot

Hungary_chi_1 <- filter(Hungary_chi, Hungary_chi$emplrel != "NA")
ggplot(Hungary_chi_1) +
  geom_bar(aes(x = gndr, fill = emplrel), position="fill") + 
  ggtitle("Employment form within different genders") +
  xlab("Gender of a person") +
  ylab("Employment form") +
  labs(fill = "Employment form")

With the help of visualization, we can interpret the results: On the graph we see that within both genders being an employee is the dominant form of employment. However, even though the difference is not crucial, among males the self-employment is more popular than among females.

Now we can move to the test to check the hypotheses. However, before running the real chi-squared test, we check the assumptions that should be met:

  • Each observation in the data contribute exclusively to one group -> observations are independent
table(Hungary_chi_1)
##         emplrel
## gndr     Employee Self-employed Working for own family business
##   Male        574            50                              15
##   Female      822            42                              14

We check whether the data contains no expected counts less than 1, so we look at the expected frequencies. Here we also check if there are >5 observations per each sell:

Hungary_chi_2 <- table(Hungary_chi_1)
chisq.test(Hungary_chi_2)$exp
##         emplrel
## gndr     Employee Self-employed Working for own family business
##   Male   588.0316       38.7528                        12.21556
##   Female 807.9684       53.2472                        16.78444

Now, when we checked our data, we can run the test:

chisq.test(Hungary_chi_2)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  Hungary_chi_2
## X-squared = 7.3151, df = 2, p-value = 0.0258

We see that the p-value equals 0,0258 (p<0,05) -> the test is significant, so there is an association between the gender of a person and his/her employment form. We reject the null hypothesis. However, to inspect these differences in more details we need to look at the residuals:

chires <- chisq.test(Hungary_chi_2)
chires$stdres
##         emplrel
## gndr      Employee Self-employed Working for own family business
##   Male   -2.693108      2.450325                        1.057349
##   Female  2.693108     -2.450325                       -1.057349

We see that some values of the residuals lie outside of +-1,96, so they are significant (with p-value<0,5). These are: male employees, self-employed males, female employees, self-employed females. Thus, the forms of self-employment and being an employee have an association with the gender of a person. While working for own family business do not give us proper information for making conclusions.

We can also visualize the residuals for easier interpretation:

corrplot(chires$stdres, is.cor = FALSE)

The visualization allows us to see the positive association between the self-employment and male gender, as well as between female gender and working as an employee.

Overall, gender of a person and employment form do correlate. Males are more likely to be self-employed than females, while females prefer the general employment. Thus, with the help of chi-squared test, we have rejected the null-hypothesis and proved that the variables are dependent

T-test

Select columns, that can be used in T-test

Hu_v1.0 <- Hungary [c("iagmr", "iagpnt")]
Hu_v1.0 <- na.omit(Hu_v1.0)
Hu_v2.0 <- Hu_v1.0[Hu_v1.0$iagmr != "No ideal age" & Hu_v1.0$iagmr != "Should never get married" & Hu_v1.0$iagpnt != "No ideal age", ]

Deleting open-ended answers (and left only numeric) to use statistical methods in future.

Renaming columns for better layout

Hu_v3.0 <- Hu_v2.0 %>%
  rename(ideal_marriage_age=iagmr, ideal_parenthood_age=iagpnt)

The data format may look a little strange, but we assume that for all numbers from the first column the factor is ideal_marriage_age, and for the second - factor is ideal_parenthood_age.

Data type - factor. Need to change it.

Hu_v3.0$ideal_marriage_age <- as.numeric(as.character(Hu_v3.0$ideal_marriage_age))

## [1] "numeric"

Everything is fine.

Creating a boxplot

boxplot(Hu_v3.0)

State the hypothesis. Null hypothesis: the mean values of ideal_marriage_age and ideal_parenthood_age are equal. Alternative hypothesis: the mean values of ideal_marriage_age and ideal_parenthood_age not equal. If during the t.test p will be < 0.05, we will reject the null hypothesis. If during the t.test p will be > 0.05, we will fail to reject the null hypothesis.

Specifying substantive hypothesis: we expect that ideal parenthood age will be higher that marriage one, as it will be unreasonable to prefer have kids before marriage.

Check assumption of normality: Normality tests.

QQplot test

ggplot(Hu_v3.0, aes(sample = ideal_marriage_age)) +
  stat_qq() +
  stat_qq_line()

ggplot(Hu_v3.0, aes(sample = ideal_parenthood_age)) +
  stat_qq() +
  stat_qq_line()

On both plots, the points significantly deviate from the line. This indicates that the variable is not normally allocated. + Also we can see right skew of data outlines in both cases.

Determine normality with describe function

Hu_v4.0 <- describe(Hu_v3.0)
Hu_v4.0<- Hu_v4.0 %>%  select(-vars,-n,-sd,-trimmed,-mad,-range,-se,-mean,-median,-min,-max)
Hu_v4.0
##                      skew kurtosis
## ideal_marriage_age   0.38     1.10
## ideal_parenthood_age 0.55     1.83

Skew is large in both cases, but the more significant is that Kurtosis in both cases is > than +-1, so the distribution is not normal.

Shapiro-Wilk tests of normality.

Test #1 Null hypothesis: The data is normally distributed. Alternative hypothesis: The data is not normally distributed.

shapiro.test(Hu_v3.0$ideal_marriage_age)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  Hu_v3.0$ideal_marriage_age
## W = 0.95819, p-value < 2.2e-16

In this case p < 0.00000024 < 0.05, so we reject the null hypothesis and assume, that data is not normally distributed.

Test #2 Null hypothesis: The data is normally distributed. Alternative hypothesis: The data is not normally distibuted.

shapiro.test(Hu_v3.0$ideal_parenthood_age)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  Hu_v3.0$ideal_parenthood_age
## W = 0.95867, p-value < 2.2e-16

In this case p < 0.00000024 < 0.05, so we reject the null hypothesis and assume, that data is not normally distributed.

For both variables, the distribution in not normal for sure. However, it is not a big problem, since T-test in quite robust to non-normality if the sample is large. But we need to remember, that in this case Type 1 risk increases.

Testing: Variance equality Simple calculations:

var(Hu_v3.0$ideal_parenthood_age)
## [1] 14.09916
var(Hu_v3.0$ideal_marriage_age)
## [1] 11.17243

So it is obvious, that variances are not equal.

Time to perform T-test. Since we have to check independent samples, which have not equal variance, the best option - is to use Welch t-test.

Let’s remind hypothesis: Null hypothesis: the mean values of ideal_marriage_age and ideal_parenthood_age are equal. Alternative hypothesis: the mean values of ideal_marriage_age and ideal_parenthood_age not equal.

t.test(Hu_v3.0$ideal_marriage_age, Hu_v3.0$ideal_parenthood_age, paired = FALSE, var.equal = FALSE) 
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Hu_v3.0$ideal_marriage_age and Hu_v3.0$ideal_parenthood_age
## t = -11.638, df = 2883.3, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -1.787890 -1.272302
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  25.28659  26.81669

since p < 0.00000024 < 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis. S values of sample are not equal. Since t= -11.638, the difference is statistically significant.

Effect size:

cohensD(Hu_v3.0$ideal_marriage_age, Hu_v3.0$ideal_parenthood_age)
## [1] 0.4304447

So, Effect size variable = 0.4304447, so the effect size is medium.

Now let’s double check the result with non-parametric Wilcoxon Rank-Sum Test.

Null hypothesis: the mean values of ideal_marriage_age and ideal_parenthood_age are equal. Alternative hypothesis: the mean values of ideal_marriage_age and ideal_parenthood_age not equal.

wilcox.test(Hu_v3.0$ideal_marriage_age, Hu_v3.0$ideal_parenthood_age, paired = FALSE, conf.int = TRUE)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  Hu_v3.0$ideal_marriage_age and Hu_v3.0$ideal_parenthood_age
## W = 808108, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -1.999948 -1.000043
## sample estimates:
## difference in location 
##              -1.000001

since p < 0.00000024 < 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis. So mean values of ideal_marriage_age and ideal_parenthood_age not equal. This corresponds to the results of the Welch t-test.

ANOVA

For one-way ANOVA test we decided to analyze relationship between the Age of first marriage (mrage) and the Place of living (domicil). Thus, we took a numeric and categorical variables. So, we creating a subset with necessary variables and exclude all NAs.

mar <- hu [c("mrage", "domicil")]
mar1 <- na.omit(mar)

Thus, our substantial hypothesis is the following: We expect the difference between the marriage ages of people who live in big cities and small towns and villages, as the second ones tend to have more traditional views and less opportunities (like ability to get higher education or build a career).

Now, we want to see the distribution of answers among participants.

ggplot(mar1) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(domicil, fill=domicil)) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  coord_flip()

As we can observe, unfortunately, the number of participants from different places of residence is highly unequal. So in order to decrease bias we used filter function. Thus, we excluded people, who live in a “farm or home in countryside”, as the it is too small.

hu_aov <- filter(mar1, mar1$domicil != "Farm or home in countryside")

Now, let’s proceed to the boxplot with corrected dataset.

ggplot(hu_aov) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(x=domicil, y=mrage, fill=domicil)) +
  xlab("Place of living") +
  ylab("Age of the first marriage ") +
  ggtitle("Place of living and First marriage age Distribution") +
  guides(legend = "none")

The difference seems to be small, but we should check it by the tests. After we defined the variables, we can state hypotheses. H0: All means are equal => there is no difference between mean ages of the first marriage among different places of residence. Ha: There is at least one difference among means. So, probably at least one type of residence has higher or smaller age of the first marriage.

Attention please! As we mentioned earlier, sample here is unequal, so suburbs or outskirt of big city is significantly smaller than others. This means that results might be biased.

Next, we have to check the homogeneity of variances, in order to be sure that we can conduct ANOVA test. We prefer Levene’s test for this case. So, we have the following hypotheses. H0: The variances are homogeneous => variances are equal Ha: Variances are not homogeneous => there is at least one difference among variances

leveneTest(mrage ~ domicil, data = hu_aov)
## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = median)
##         Df F value Pr(>F)
## group    3  0.8837 0.4489
##       1111

From the output above we can see that the p-value (0.4489) is higher than the significance level of 0.05. So we cannot reject the null hypothesis => This means that we can assume the homogeneity of variances.

Now, let’s check the Normality assumption

ggplot(hu_aov, aes(mrage)) +
  geom_histogram()

According to the graph, we can see, that “age of marriage” (mrage) variable distributed not normally.

describeBy(hu_aov, hu_aov$domicil)
## 
##  Descriptive statistics by group

Here we check the normality for each of 4 subsets of age_of_marriage by domicil. And in each one the distribution in not normal, because skew do not belong to [-0.5; 0.5].

In spite the absence of normality assumption, we we can try to run the one-way ANOVA test for our variables.

anova <- aov(mrage ~ domicil, data = hu_aov)
tidy(anova)
## # A tibble: 2 x 6
##   term         df  sumsq meansq statistic p.value
##   <chr>     <dbl>  <dbl>  <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1 domicil       3   127.   42.3      2.17  0.0905
## 2 Residuals  1111 21718.   19.5     NA    NA
summary(anova)
##               Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)  
## domicil        3    127   42.33   2.165 0.0905 .
## Residuals   1111  21718   19.55                 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

P-value here is significantly bigger than 0.05 => we cannot reject the null hypothesis (that all means are equal). However, we can’t trust to this test, as the distribution of variables is not normal => there are might be a biased

This way, to double-check the results of F-test we run the Non-parametric test

kruskal.test(mrage ~ domicil, data = hu_aov)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  mrage by domicil
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 8.7921, df = 3, p-value = 0.03219

The output here shows that p-value is smaller that 0.05 => that proves that our previous test was biased. So we reject the null hypothesis. It assumes that there is a difference among marriage ages of people from differenr places of residence.

To sum up one-way ANOVA test, we’d like to check the effect size.

kruskal_effsize(data = hu_aov, mrage ~ domicil)
## # A tibble: 1 x 5
##   .y.       n effsize method  magnitude
## * <chr> <int>   <dbl> <chr>   <ord>    
## 1 mrage  1115 0.00521 eta2[H] small

As we may see, that effect size is small.

Post hoc test performance (since the variances are not equal)

As we may see, all cases are not statistically significant. This way, we may conclude that there is no difference between variables.

Conclusion

To sum up, we conducted several tests to check our hypotheses on socio-demographic characteristics of Hungarian citizens. With the help of chi-squared test we found out that there is an overall correlation between the gender of a person and his/her form of employment. For example, Hungarian males more frequently become self-employed than do females. Then, with the help of t-test we found that the ideal marital age of a person and ideal age of becoming a parent are not equal. In general, ideal age of becoming a parent comes later than the perfect marital age. Finally, we checked our last assumption on the relationship between the age of first marriage and person’s place of living, using ANOVA test. There, we found out that place of living does not reflect muh the marital age (however, the small correlation exists). Thus, we analyzed different features peculiar for Hungarian citizens

Description of variables

We decided to chose the following variables:

continuous stfgov (ordinal) - How satisfied with the national government stfeco (ordinal) - How satisfied with present state of economy in country stfdem (ordinal) - How satisfied with the way democracy works in country All these variables have the same answer scale that starts from “Extremely dissatisfied”, than follows as 1 to 9 spectrum and ends with “Extremely satisfied”.

lrscale(interval) - Placement on left/right political views scale from “Left” to 1 - 9 spectrum, and then to “Right”. To make these variables exclusively numeric (this is necessary for the correlation matrix), we changed the outside answers from words to numbers: 0 and 10, respectively.

categorical gvintcz (ordinal) - Does government take into account the interest of all citizens (from “Not at all” to a “Great deal”)

Finally, we exclude lines with NA variables (thus we loose 323 rows from original set) and here it is our subset(table).

Interpretation of descriptive statistics

First of all, for each variable (that are presented in the first column), tha data is not skewed (since coefficient<+-1).So highly likely the data is close to normal distribution Than, by looking at kurtosis, it can be noted, that the distribution for all variables has a fairly smooth peak. Mean and median for first 4 variables are really close to each other (~5). This generally suggests that people on average have moderate (~5/10) satisfaction with government, economy and democracy, and also have approximately equal numbers of both left and right views (with a slight margin towards the right). If we look at their opinion on whether the government takes into account the opinion of citizens, then the average indicators will not be high (THey do, but quite a bit=“some”. ~2/5 median and 2.43/5 mean).

Our expectations:

Before we proceed to the analysis, we have to state our expectations.

We assume that there will be a positive correlation between satisfaction with government and political views of a person, so the more right views one has, the more he/she will be satisfied with the government (Because the Hungarian government has been more right-wing for the last 10 years).

We also expect that there might be a positive correlation between satisfaction with government and satisfaction with a present state of economy in country. We think that for people one of the criteria for the success of a government is a good economy and vice versa: bad economy is fail of government.

The third correlation we expect is also positive and a little bit obvious. So, we suppose that, as in previous cases, the more satisfied person with the way democracy works in country, the more he or she will be satisfied with the government.

And the last, but not the least correlation we expect is a positive correlation of continuous and categorical variables, namely the government satisfaction and believes that government takes into account all citizens interests. As people who are really dissatisfied with it probably believe that government don’t take their views and problems into account.

Interpretation of the model fit

Now, when we have chosen the model, which fits the data better, we can proceed to the interpretation. For this we look at the summary for the model.

Satisfaction with democracy: If other variables are constant, people who score an additional point higher on satisfaction with democracy are predicted to score 0.48 higher on satisfaction with government, on average.

Satisfaction with economy: If other variables are constant, people who score an additional point higher on satisfaction with economy are predicted to score 0.47 higher on satisfaction with government, on average

Peoples’ view on the idea that government takes into account interests of the people: Let us look at one of the coefficients here. For example, we may say that if other variables are constant, people who think that government takes into account interests of people a lot are predicted to score 0,86 higher on satisfaction with government than the reference group (ones who consider that government does not take interests of people into account), on average

Regression equation

Now we can write out the regression equation with all the coefficients

Satisfaction with government = -0.23 + 0.48 Dem. Sat. + 0.47Econ. Sat + 0.12 Very little + 0.5 Some + 0.9 A lot + 1.1 A great deal

If people answer “Some” on question “how much does the state take into account the interests of people”, we predict they will access satisfaction with government 0.508 points higher (on average). Conclusion

To sum up, in this project we have tried to look on the different factors, which may have influenced on the Hungarian citizens’ satisfaction with the government. We have found out that peoples’ satisfaction with democracy and economy may predict their contentment with the government. Moreover, we have found that peoples’ views on whether government takes into account interests of citizens also influence their satisfaction. For instance, those people who consider that government does this a lot (a great deal) are more likely to be satisfied with the governmental policies.

Project 4: Moderation Model

Research area & question

In this project we continued to analyze the political views of Hungarian citizens. Thus, we tried to explore the data more.

Theoretical framework:

Christensen and Lægreid argued, including drawing on previous research, that satisfaction with democracy is an indirect indicator of how well a regime is performing. [1] And also, Zhengxu Wang, in his research based on real data, mentioned a pattern that significant economic growth has a positive effect on citizens’ assessment of their government.[2] We plan to test in our work how well these ideas work. Thus, by working with data, we plan to pay attention on satisfaction with economy and democracy as well as other variables we found important. Finally our research question will be the following: What factors and to what extent predict citizens’ satisfaction with their government?

Description of variables

continuous stfgov (ordinal) - How satisfied with the national government stfeco (ordinal) - How satisfied with present state of economy in country stfdem (ordinal) - How satisfied with the way democracy works in country All these variables have the same answer scale that starts from “Extremely dissatisfied”, than follows as 1 to 9 spectrum and ends with “Extremely satisfied”.

categorical gvintcz (ordinal) - Does government take into account the interest of all citizens (from “Not at all” to a “Great deal”) pbldmn binary (ordinal) - Did the respondent participate in protests against the government. (“Yes” or “no”)

Mode function:

function.mode <- function(x) {
  theonly <- na.omit(unique(x))
  theonly[which.max(tabulate(match(x, theonly,  nomatch = NA_integer_, incomparables = NULL)))]
}

Additive model

First, we create an additive model without any moderation effect. We add 2 continuous predictors and one categorical. We also center the continuous predictors.

For our model we decided to take the same variables as were presented in the previous project. Just to remind you: the outcome variable was people’s satisfaction with government. There were also two continuous predictors: people’s satisfaction with democracy; people’s satisfaction with economy and one categorical predictor - peoples’ view on the idea that government takes into account interests of the people. The correlations between variables were significant and positive. In particular, 0,84 for people’s satisfaction with democracy and people’s satisfaction with government; 0,81 for people’s satisfaction with economy and people’s satisfaction with government.

So, here, alike the previous project, we expect to see the correlation between the people’s satisfaction with government and their satisfaction with economy, democracy of the country, as well as with their view on whether the government takes into account interests os people. We expect that all these variables will have a positive relationship with the outcome variable. So, the model with all the three predictors will fit the data better

Besides, we look for the standartized coefficients and margins

Interpretation of the model:

We may see that the 3rd model fits the data better. First, we look at the Degrees of freedom (Df), which tells us that in the last model we estimate 4 parameters. Also, RSS tells us how much was left unexplained, therefore the smaller RSS is better for model fit (in the last model, it is 2102). Besides that, we can see that stars (referring to F-statistic) tell us the last model is better than the previous models. So, we have seen the 3rd model has the best fit

We also look at the coefficients. We can see that if other variables are held constant, a person is predicted to score -0,22 in terms of satisfaction with government. Holding everything constant, If the person scores an additional point on satisfaction with economy, he is predicted to score 0,47 more on satisfaction with government (on average). Alike, is person is satisfied with democracy, he is going to score 0,48 more on satisfaction with government on average, holding other variables constant. As for the view on whether the government takes into account interests of people: if person, for example, consider that government do a great deal in this regard he/she is predicted to score 1,09 more on satisfaction with government (on average, holding other variables constant)

Next, we look at the centering. Here the coefficients stay the same, however, the intercept has changed.Now it is much higher (4.27 compared to -0,22). Now, let’s look at the standardized coefficients. Here the intercepts equals zero and the coefficients have slightly changed. For the satisfaction with economy it is now 0,399, for satisfaction with democracy - 0,47. They also became lower for categorical predictor: for example, it is now only 0,069 for the view that government do take into account interests of people a great deal.

Now, let’s look at the margins. These are 0,47 for satisfaction with economy, 0,48 for satisfaction with democracy and 1,09 for the view that government do a great deal taking into account interests of people

We expect that the view whether the government takes into account the intersts of people will influence th relation between satisfacyion with economy and satisfaction with government. As we can see at the plots. The interaction effect is can be met there, but not fully. In case of civic interests taken in account and economy satisfaction the interaction is obvious and visible. The plot shows how people who claim that government cares about civic interests a more supportive and satisfied with a government and economy. Their curve is higher than others, so this variable has an impact on the interaction of stfgov & stfeco. It is especially noticeable in compare of lines “A great deal” and “Not at all”.

As for the second plot. Here the moderation is quite weak, but still present. So, we may see that people who participated in meetings tend to be less satisfied with the government in addition to the democracy, than those who didn’t visit meeting last year at all.

Conclusion

To sum up, we may say that we found some factors that predict citizens’ satisfaction with their government. We explored impact of satisfaction with country’s economy and democracy, and also some categorical predictors, such as participation in public demonstration and believe that government cares about your interests on the people’s satisfaction with government. We can claim that our expectations were proved, because, in fact, all the variables had an effect on the satisfaction with government. We also looked at some interaction effects. For example, how the view that government takes people’s opinion into account influences the relationship between the satisfaction with economy and satisfaction with government. Though we cannot say that the effect was very strong, there were observed some correlations. For the participation in public demostration’s influence on the relationship between satisfaction with democracy and satisfaction with government the effect was even smaller. However, still, our last model with interaction effects explained the data best, so we can conclude, our hypotheses were confirmed.
